============================================================

Done. Here's the summary of what I found:

**Root cause:** The 8-word guard added in iteration 20 (`words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)`) rejects the candidate `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)` because `/` is missing from the separator whitelist.

**What happened:**
1. Lines 54–55 of the OCR (`SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` + `/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`) are correctly merged by the continuation pre-merge (line 55 starts with `/`).
2. The merged 10-word candidate then hits the 8-word filter — which only allows ` + `, ` : `, ` & ` as exceptions, not ` / `.
3. Since the pre-merge consumed line 55, `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` alone never exists as a standalone candidate either.
4. With the real title gone, the algorithm falls back to `FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)` — a truncated OCR fragment from the *previous* recipe on the same page.
5. The truncation-detection code can't fire because `SAFFRON` never enters the candidate pool.

**Fix:** Add `/` to the exception regex: `!/ [+:&/] /.test(text)`.
