{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01AmCgsKuyYbHUGf1tfgG2HB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a good understanding of the failing case. Let me analyze it:\n\n**Failing file:** `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D).real.txt`\n\n**Expected title:** `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK : COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`\n\n**The content structure:**\n\nThe OCR text begins with content from a PREVIOUS recipe (SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS VARIATION 1), with corrupted/partial title \"BUNS\" on line 1. The actual target recipe \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\" appears much later in the document at lines 54-55:\n\n\nThe real title is split across two lines in the OCR output — line 54 has `SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK` and line 55 continues with `/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)`. The algorithm needs to handle this multi-line title while skipping past the corrupted opening lines that belong to a different recipe entirely. So \"BUNS\" doesn't actually qualify as garbled—it's under 20 characters but has a reasonable vowel ratio and no other red flags. The `findBurstEnd` function requires both conditions to be true, so it would stop immediately at that line since \"BUNS\" fails the garbled check.\n\nWith `burstEnd` at 0, the algorithm processes everything from the start. \"BUNS\" itself is all caps, a single word under 25 characters, and not a section label, so it stands alone as a capsCoalesced entry. The next line \"ssekart\" isn't all caps, so there's no coalescing between them. When checking for continuation merging, \"ssekart\" doesn't start with the special character pattern, so \"BUNS\" remains isolated. The only candidate for \"BUNS\" is the single-word filter.\n\nNow I'm validating whether \"BUNS\" passes the hard filters—it's 4 characters long, not an ingredient, doesn't start with a number, and checking the garble detection: it has 4 letters with one vowel (U), giving a vowel ratio of 0.25, which is acceptable. There's no lowercase-to-uppercase transition, no leading lowercase, and no mid-text sentence structure, so it's not flagged as garbled. The length and ingredient checks both pass.\n\nBut then I realize \"BUNS\" is a single word that exists in the NON_TITLE_WORDS set, which means it gets filtered out by the hard filters. So \"BUNS\" would be rejected, which is correct. Now I need to check what happens with the other lines in the actual title section.\n\nLooking at lines 54 and 55, I see \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK\" followed by \"/ COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\". Since the second line starts with a slash, these get merged into one complete title: \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\". Let me verify this passes the filters—it's under 80 characters, doesn't look like an ingredient or metadata, and doesn't start with a number.\n\nNow checking the garbled text detection: the string has mixed case and a slash, but the garbled check looks for a period followed by whitespace and a letter, which this doesn't have. It also passes the other filters—no cooking instructions, no pipes, only one slash (under the limit of 2), and it's not a bullet or section label.\n\nBut here's where it fails: counting the words in \"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\" gives 10 words, and the filter rejects anything with 8+ words unless it contains a `+`, `:`, or `&` separator. Since this title only has a `/`, it gets filtered out—and that's the bug. allowed set ` + `, ` : `, or ` & `. So the merged candidate would fail the filter. Now I'm tracing through the pre-merge step to understand how lines get combined — it looks like the code iterates through the coalesced lines and merges adjacent ones together, but I need to see where that logic actually checks the next line's text. I see the issue now — the merged title contains a forward slash, but the hard filters only exempt