rigger. So the parenthetical \"(VARIATION 1)\" passes the all-caps check since \"VARIATION\" is uppercase, which means `stripParentheticalGloss` returns the full text unchanged — \"FRON WHEAT BUNS (VARIATION 1)\" becomes the candidate. Now I'm checking if this passes the hard filters, starting with word count at 5 words.\n\nFor `isStructuralHeading`, I'm verifying that the all-caps letters still qualify and that the significant words filter (those with more than one uppercase letter) includes \"FRON\", \"WHEAT\", and \"BUNS\".\n\nNow I'm working through the truncation detection logic... The issue is that the truncation detection can't find \"SAFFRON\" as a longer word ending with \"FRON\" because the correct title fails the hard filters and never makes it into the candidates array in the first place. So the algorithm ends up returning the wrong structural heading instead of the actual correct title. The fix is straightforward—I need to add `/` to the allowed separator characters in the 8-word filter so that titles with forward slashes aren't incorrectly rejected. However, the user specifically asked me not to modify code files, only to write the feedback. Let me review the iteration context and compile the key findings into the feedback document now.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2995,"cache_read_input_tokens":44100,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2995},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"eb533174-fed4-4e6a-8d51-5fccd85ce376","uuid":"9ef98b26-7cac-4425-994c-e71b7e1e8af9"}
