{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01WEaq3BUqkEHWuPMZryhgCe","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I can see exactly what changed between iteration 19 and iteration 20. The key change that could break SAFFRON is:\n\n```javascript\n// Lines with ≥8 words are almost certainly body text, not titles.\n// Exception: multi-title compounds with \" + \", \" : \", or \" & \" separators are allowed.\nif (words.length >= 8 && !/ [+:&] /.test(text)) return false;\n```\n\nThis 8-word filter was ADDED in iteration 20. In iteration 19, this filter didn't exist. So the merged candidate `\"SAFFRON WHEAT BUNS WITH QUARK / COTTAGE CHEESE (VARIATION D)\"` would have been allowed through in iter 19 (no 8-word filter), but is now blocked in iter 20 (≥8 words and `/` is not in `+:&`).\n\n\nBut I'm realizing there's a discrepancy here — if the merged candidate in iter 19 had a `/`, how did it end up as `:` in the expected output? Either the test harness is normalizing the separator, or something else is happening with how the candidates are being processed.\n\nLet me look at the test runner to see how it's actually comparing these values.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3284,"cache_read_input_tokens":59073,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3284},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"eb533174-fed4-4e6a-8d51-5fccd85ce376","uuid":"d7c7586a-0b7a-4f6a-b0e8-80666a5b69ef"}
